Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 countries of the euro area was higher than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 percent was recorded, the European Community statistics office located in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the interest rate by saying that lowering interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so as not to have to intervene on this subject at a later date.
In Germany, the rate of inflation of 3.3 per cent is a record over the last twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Grain futures market shares rose 88 percent and the price of soybeans also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world’s oil price rose 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, over the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup warns of government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Young Democrats Alliance) increased significantly at the beginning of December, with the largest number of supporters since 2002, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never seen such low socialist support, at 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
On the faithful voters certain to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous low point, the proportion of those who considered that the economic situation in the country was particularly serious has never been so high, it amounts to 41 percent and according to 46 percent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the next year, the majority of the population expects an aggravation and only a tenth expects an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those polled, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, said the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
Thirteen percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society that believes that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without a change in government.
While after last October's riots, 35 percent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, at present this rate is only 20 percent, and the relative majority (33 percent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents said they would certainly vote, and the additional 20 per cent said they would probably vote.
To make a comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of those polled would certainly participate and 15 percent would probably participate.
74 percent of people would say no to higher education tuition fees, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look at only the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters respectively would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the Budaörs commercial triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, with the difference that this year the VAT rate did not rise.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a value increase of well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had “already soared” at grocery stores last December, have no longer risen sharply from the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded by at least 91 forints the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey fillet, nuts and poppy rose sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo at only 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was surprising to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the delivered bottle of two liters of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the delivered bottle included.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of her Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent, respectively.
Comparing last year’s most expensive basket and this year’s cheapest basket, we find a 12 percent difference while the difference between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices increased by 1,480 forints on average.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, although the impact of the VAT rate increase was already noticeable in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has puzzled the trade, the hypermarkets could not clearly determine what margin to apply on products because they were unable to predict the impact of the change in prices on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in the Daily Basket prices has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the prices of the cheapest increased by 1,284 forints as well.
Approaching the two Christmas seasons, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some staple feeds, the Statistical Institute found a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the evidence, the flour suppliers are in a stronger position than the egg suppliers because they have managed to make the brutal price increases accepted also by the multinationals.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take the food of long conservation by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the cash registers of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies of not even reaching the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical staff do not help block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected on a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured person from a serious car accident was released from the hospital but had to return shortly after due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Center for Epidemiology.
That is to say, it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-antibiotic-resistant bacterium that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacteria can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, those with small weights or those with a weakened organism.
According to the medical director of the János hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Especially not to confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only there or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics tailored to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favorable to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and in nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and isolate MRSA patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these reviews.
Most cases only see the light of day if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are Hungarian guidelines also for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be performed to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient care and in basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferates from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and wear protective masks. However, there are significant shortcomings in hospitals in this area as well.
MRSA proliferates through infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient can not always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the patients should be away from each other by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, save on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government Project Against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA represents an exorbitant expense for the social security funds, which is why the fight against this infection is everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to the published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who was the author of a fatal accident, was not intoxicated.
The official statement regarding the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It can be ruled out that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has resigned from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, said Attila Morvai, spokesman for the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding was made.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which has already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before getting behind the wheel.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the police station in the 22nd arrondissement crushed a 55-year-old man who found himself facing him when he turned, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos street in the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(In fact, crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance, according to the Highway Code, a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians through.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his position and he applied for retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident greatly upset him.
The investigation into this case is being carried out by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates responsible for conducting the investigation.
