Bulgaria, a paradise for the EU real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the most fashionable target in Eastern Europe with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nessebar but they are more and more looking for a building in the area of Kavarna and Balcik as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very inexpensive corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, offers attractive opportunities as well, retail and office spaces promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer season and the winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are looking at the same time to change their lives, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. On the shores of the Black Sea and in the most renowned ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria has been cited among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of realizing a medium or long-term added value.
The price of real estate in the capital is constantly rising as a result of increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially outweighs the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Six Percent Hungarian
According to the communication of Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of professionals end on Tuesday, however, on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is expected to define the efforts to be made after the emission reduction period defined by the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
At the moment, vigorous discussions are being held between developing and developed countries on this issue.
The United States also reported that, for the time being, it did not want to discuss exact figures, while it was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from 1990 levels by 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committing, excluding emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board, likely under the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), said Piac es Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Water Minister Gábor Fodor confirms the EU's ambition to retain its role as flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent from the level reached in 1990 by 2020, regardless of the success of the signing of the “post-2012 agreement”, and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to make commitments tailored to their responsibilities and capacities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the Kyoto Protocol countries had aimed at a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time made the commitment by 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the commitments of reduction below the values provided for in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international body of scientific emission reductions, whose need was emphasized in the international IPCC report.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase of the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees celsius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British military recruits on YouTube
British army units are communicating, on the video-sharing site, recordings made during its operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, it was the British Air Force (RAF) that became passionate about YouTube: the special units intervening in Afghanistan uploaded video footage of the operations carried out against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to London or uploaded by compatriots over the Internet.
The political message is unavoidable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net by this route and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and is communicating videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defense, they were also used to make known to the general public the real objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
Propaganda published in this way costs practically nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, said Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special form the merits of military operations decided by the government.
The Americans played a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been passed on the sharing site that also show, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already gone on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British army is only recently eager to upload these videos.
The Americans recruit a little differently using the free-to-play shooter America's Army, in which the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
