The Ministry of Agriculture will hold a reception on January 20 to celebrate the new year, Christmas will not take place.
The reception will be held at Vajdahunyad Castle, located at City Wood, and according to the communication of the ministry, 1,000 forints per person are calculated for the one hundred guests.
According to the press service, this will be a very simple cocktail to which only foreign diplomats accredited in Hungary will be invited.
These cocktails, organized every year, are started by a few words of welcome from the minister followed by a modest meal.
The Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Ministry of Education and Culture do not celebrate Christmas at all, the respective press services have informed [origo].
The press service of the Ministry of the Environment did not know the price of the official Christmas party.
However, more than four hundred people were invited to the party held at the Museum of Decorative Art.
Mega Strike Forces Gather
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will constitute, on Friday, their strike commission, which will be responsible for coordinating Monday's indefinite strike.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protest will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the law on health insurance, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause major traffic jams because rail traffic will be stopped almost completely and employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 13h.
The unions of the league will announce, Friday afternoon, the details of their strike on Monday, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike commission of LIGA - MOSZ will also be constituted, it will serve as coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general assembly of protesters will be held and, starting Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work indefinitely if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in parliament on the law on health funds, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not pass the Health Funds Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the strike call.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike commissions will meet and decide what to do next.
According to the National Assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the Health Funds Act will not take place until late in the evening, or even at night.
Due to the strike scheduled for Monday, major traffic jams are planned: the railways will stop work indefinitely and during the morning part of the public transport in Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are at risk of being stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half of the road will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the strike call, the list of which is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations report an indefinite strike, others have declared a temporary work stoppage.
Until Thursday afternoon the M<0xC3><0x81>V (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) were unable to reach an agreement on minimum services, but, as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 13h, Budapest airport between 7h and 9h in the morning, the Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union called for a strike for 8 hours and 2 hours respectively during 2 hours.
The National Association of Physicians will strike across the country alternately, the Union of Health and Social Sector Employees (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will strike a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires the government to withdraw its proposal on health reform and submit a new conception to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating retirement to be put in place from next year be introduced in several stages.
The third demand is for a guarantee of retirement before the legal age, which would allow for the transfer into the system of the functions that deserve it before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ), attached to the Unions of the League, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning the secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, formed last August, with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary) increases, in several aspects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning", the company points out that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic clashes may occur as a result of the aggravation of the already existing ethnic tension between the gypsy and non-gypsy population of Hungary".
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard’s political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: “Public actors passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groups that based a political strategy on the dispute between Gypsies and Hungarians”.
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened, and aggressive conflicts are more likely, they say.
However, according to the research institute, under the effect of the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the activity of the Hungarian Guard "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular with regard to confidence in the stability and democratic maturity of the country".
They recall that, following a greater publicity given to the reorganization of Hungarian radical and far-right groups since the fall of 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 calling themselves the "national self-defense association".
“The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civilian organization while they publicly declare the preparation of their adherents for defense missions (disaster, national defense, defense of order), armed if necessary, in addition, evoking the incapacity of the police, of the army, in other words, of the state,” they added.
They pointed out that everything was going according to the method that, based on the resentment of the political society and the parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions from a civilian point of view.
The emphasis on civil character and association status therefore serves only to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering these associations in court but they also constitute a political strategy.
The analysis indicates that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor that also increases the risk compared to neighboring relationships.
“In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and the ultranationalist political actors of some neighbouring countries wish to justify their anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This affects the political stability of the region,” they added.
According to the research institute, the constitution of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern Central Europe, political risks have increased throughout the region.
As they say, the operation of the Hungarian Guard resembles, for example, the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard whose constitution was declared by the Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The numerous Roma riots that broke out in a Sofia neighborhood (Kraszna Poljana) led to the constitution of the Bulgarian Guard.
