The party is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become commonplace to reorganize the working days whose number will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the United States either.
Hungarian law distinguishes between national and state holidays and rest days.
Days of rest are often related to religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year ending and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that New Year's Eve can rest quietly.
Moreover, in a year, we have a total of eleven festivals marked in red.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, as is October 23, which is the commemorative day of the Revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1 is Labor Day and on November 1 and 2, we remember members of our family and friends who have died.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
The days of our state, national or religious holidays rarely falling on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has made specific regulations on the replacement days of the days before or after the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and all their employees, civil servants and people working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service companies, institutions that are constantly rotating and in service, by their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to experiences the majority of people do rather overtime or take vacations that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home for four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25 will be a working day to have a rest day on Friday, May 2.
Another change is scheduled for October 23: Saturday, October 18 will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
Six futile things that can annoy colleagues terribly
Emails we forget to send, voice messages we never receive, innocent lies that annoy us almost more: these are things that “embellish” the daily life of a workplace.
The question is whether we get used to these problems or take up the challenge and consciously avoid ambiguous situations, causing trouble to others.
Examples.
“Excuse me, I forgot to tell you that we called you from the marketing department,” a colleague tells you.
That you missed a date?
At best he is sorry and tries to make things right by calling the marketing department to tell them that he forgot to pass the message (this is the less common solution).
In most cases, this is arranged with an apology.
Before having painful explanations, it is useful to think about how you will be able to cause unpleasant moments to your colleagues and make efforts to avoid them.
Are you borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There’s nothing more annoying than wanting to take a file, an office tool or the phone and you don’t find them anywhere.
Remember the day before you put the stapler on the desk but it disappeared the next morning?
Do you happen to find your pen that you thought was lost on your colleague's desk?
Do not take anything from your colleagues without asking otherwise they are right to be angry with you for stealing their property.
Don’t bring envelopes, post-it in your pocket because it can be annoying that there are no more and you need them right away.
Are you talking about the privacy of colleagues?
There are no good ways to stop gossip spreading.
Who did what, with whom?
Where and why?
Don’t tell everyone your information (suppositions) about the privacy of your colleagues!
If a colleague shares his intimate secrets with you, do not abuse his trust!
Bury the shared information inside yourself and do not discuss it with your colleagues in their absence even if your colleagues are also aware of it.
Are you saying you're sick for no good reason?
When you call the office and declare yourself ill under the pretext of a heartbreaking headache because you feel bad or feel you need rest that day, think about the fact that your work, your urgent affairs, your missions in the future must be carried out by someone else in your place.
Don't get your colleagues in trouble!
If you know in advance that the next day you will not go to work or that something may happen that would force you to stay home, do not forget to warn your boss and your colleagues to prevent them from being surprised at your absence the next day.
Flirting, laughing, phone
Do you get into your work but the laughter of your colleagues tears you away brutally?
Did you unwittingly become a witness to a phone conversation that you would have been better off not listening to?
Don’t bother your colleagues with hums, chants, loud arguments (which you conduct over their heads), poundings, big words, or loud discontent.
They can disturb even if your colleagues are not immersed in a project (writing, design, organization).
Are you accusing others of wrongdoing?
If your work is not done by the deadline, you forget to send a mail or an important message, do not accuse anyone for this forgetfulness!
Do not put it on account of the possible chaos in the office or your noisy colleagues!
Recognize it if you have made a mistake and if it has presented inconveniences for others, repair the mistake!
Ask how you can fix your fault, fix the negligence!
Do you feel too at home in the office?
Putting on a jogging and slippers is comfortable at home but they are not suitable for the office!
Do not wear comfortable jogging even if your function allows it!
Do not be neglected, respect your colleagues and yourself by dressing properly, and if your function requires it by putting on pretty and elegant clothes, to go to work!
