This is the first time since the attacks of September 11 that the Central Banks of individual States have decided on such concerted action, aimed at preventing or even diminishing the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," writes Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
"Cooperative action by central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent," Baumohl said in his report.
