Cuba, the most beautiful island in the Caribbean
For visitors, it is truly an island of freedom.
Everything you expect from your vacation can be achieved if you make a good choice.
Golden and white beaches like snow, high waves or a calm sea like a pond.
Palms and all inclusive with waiters offering you on the beach a pizza, ice cream or intoxicating cocktails.
Kitesurfing, golf and roulette.
On the islands of the Caribbean Sea, you will not find this list only in its entirety, but enriched.
Now, there is only one island on which you will find much more and it is Cuba, the largest and most beautiful island of the Greater Antilles.
In the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the stronghold of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the deposit and transshipment place of the treasures that the Spanish had stolen and transported to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was built in the early 1920s.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who built it, since everything that was a crime in the US (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings were pushed and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50s of the last century, circulated on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and, in Cojímar, he had his yacht.
The stars of show business and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
What about today?
You can leave your own autograph on the walls of the Bodeguita de la Habana.
In the bar of the hotel Nacional, a luxury hotel, you will mix the cocktail of your choice.
And these cult cars still circulate in Havana, since the jigoulis and fiats once imported have already long ago, in a climate so salty and moist, rotten.
Although Havana, especially the oldest part, is substantially decrepit, nowhere else in the surroundings are there as many splendid colonial monuments as there are precisely there.
Other places become more beautiful, for example Trinidad.
Since tourism brings the money if needed, its development has the green light.
In the last fifteen years, new hotels have grown not only in Havana, but especially in Varader, on the coast of the province of Holguín, and also on small islands such as Cayo Coco, Cayo Guillermo and others.
Cuba still offers a fantasy that is unique in the world and will be appreciated especially by lovers of small trains.
The cane had returned from the extended plantations in the sugar mills on a narrow lane by small steam and motor trains.
Their rolling stock has not been renewed for decades and this is how we can see small locomotives running, contemporary ones are only in museums.
Where to direct your steps?
The majority of visitors do not miss the most well-known places.
There is no need to write much about Varadero or Havana.
Not to mention that in the property of Hemingway, already mentioned, there is a museum and that the one who loves this writer should not miss the visit.
The Vi<0xC5><0x88>ales Valley in the west of the island is one of the most picturesque corners of Cuba.
Exuberant vegetation grows on limestone soil.
Mogotes, limestone balloons, and rocks rise from the bottom of the valley, and fertile earth being trapped in their bowels, even its rotten rocks are covered with a very dense plant carpet.
The valley is probably where Cuban tobacco of the highest quality is grown.
You will be able to meet the final form of this product if you visit one of the cigar factories in Havana.
Perhaps someone will also find it interesting that this is where the Chilean episode of Major Zeman was filmed.
Trinidad
Ancient town founded shortly after the Spanish colonized the island.
It was the slave trade and the sugar trade that brought him glory and wealth.
Wealth has been embodied in the beauty and character of this small town.
Coloniální <0xC5><0xA1>pan<0xC4><0x9B>lská architecture, v<0xC3><0xBD>razn<0xC4><0x9B> ovlivn<0xC4><0x9B>ná pozd<0xC4><0x9B>j<0xC5><0xA1>ími francouzsk<0xC3><0xBD>mi osadníky, is za <0xC4><0x8D>ty<0xC5><0x99>i staletí tém<0xC4><0x9B><0xC5><0x99> nezm<0xC4><0x9B>nila.
Trinidad, located between the sea and the mountainous massif Escambray, is a place so far apart that even in the 50' of the last century, there was no road that would connect this region with the rest of the country.
This isolation allowed him to stay on the sidelines.
We didn’t build anything, and that’s why we didn’t demolish anything either, everyone just had a roof over their heads.
If you have more time than an afternoon in Trinidad, then it is also worth visiting interesting places in the surrounding area, such as the Playa Ancón beach or the Sucreries Valley.
Then, in the evening, it is customary to go to the Casa de la Música which comes alive after sunset and where the music only deafens in the early morning.
Baracoa
Some refer to this town located in the extreme east of Cuba as the most beautiful of the island.
This opinion is certainly already influenced by the path that leads there.
The two roads leading from Guantánamo must cross high and rugged mountains and cross a landscape almost unmarked by human activity.
UNESCO has inscribed the Eastern Reef of Cuba, thanks to its intact landscape, on the World Heritage List.
The best chocolate is made there, in the church, there is the cross of Christopher Columbus (in reality, it was born about a hundred years after the journey of Columbus) and from the hill where the old stronghold and the current El Castillo hotel stands, you can see several table mountains, the most famous of which is El Yunque.
About coffee, rum, cigars, the Sierra Maestra mountain range, the Bay of Sows and the Isla de Pinos island, the Tropicana cabaret, the sanctuary of the patron saint of Cuba Caridad del Cobre, the Santeria, the African religions practiced by the descendants of former slaves, about all this one could fill a lot of pages.
As they say, it’s best to see it once.
In Afghanistan, allies are passive, say Americans
The lack of troops and necessary equipment, according to the United States, affects the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
Defense Minister Robert Gates said NATO should draw up a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission to Afghanistan is not proceeding as it should, agreed in Edinburgh in Scotland the representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country.
Alongside the growing challenge from the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are also discussing future plans and allied coordination.
While the U.S. has called this week through Defense Minister Robert Gates for NATO troops to step up activity, Britain sees strengthening the Afghan government’s authority and intensifying development aid as a priority.
“The evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow residents to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," British Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The Afghan insurgent activity is, according to U.S. military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions increased by 27 percent compared to last year, up to 60 percent in the southern Helmand province.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, nearly a quarter of them in the southern part.
However, according to the United States, the allies have reached their absolute limit both in the organization and in the equipment of the troops.
Specifically, they are asking for more helicopters, soldiers and experts to train Afghan troops.
"We will have to think seriously about the concrete goals for the period ahead, as well as how to achieve them," Gates said.
NATO Secretary General Jaap de Hoop made similar remarks today.
“I’m not happy with what we have on the ground and in the air in Afghanistan.
