State debt will rise to 1 trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding Kroner 84,000 is on each Czech.
Total debt rose at the end of September to Kronor 842.7 billion.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
Thanks to a better-than-expected evolution of the state budget savings, the department reduced the projected amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
The debt of the State of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion kroner.
During the nine months of this year, therefore, it increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
As of June, it has decreased by 13.4 billion crowns.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its data on the state debt dating back to the beginning of October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 crowns rests with each Czech.
Over the past year, the state has indebted more than 111 billion crowns.
"At the moment, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit planned for next year, we could cross the border of one trillion crowns only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between 900 billion and a trillion crowns," Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladimír Pikor’s forecast is similar: “One could exceed the trillion in the course of 2009.
The exact date will depend on the next budget that is not yet known.
If it appeared that the situation on the political scene was changing, that policies were ready to save more, the date could be pushed back to 2010.
But I don’t expect this change,” he said.
Debts are growing
The debt of the state is constituted by the debts of the central government and it is generated essentially by the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
State debt is financed by treasury bonds, annuity securities, direct loans or, for example, by loans to the European Investment Bank.
The state's domestic debt has so far increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion kroner.
The foreign debt of the state has increased this year at the moment from 1.7 billion crowns to 123.3 billion crowns.
The state debt called negotiable reached at the end of September 803.3 billion kroner and as of June it decreased by 13.7 billion kroner.
The average state debt maturity was 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased year-on-year from the first to the third half by 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, a figure far too high.
Interestingly, the increase is mainly generated by annuity securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It’s bad that debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be matter to negotiate when pension reform comes,” Pikora said.
Better than we expected
It follows the government's debt financing and management strategy for 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion kroner this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected evolution of the savings of the state budget, the ministry reduced the amount expected to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is essentially constituted by the deficit of the state budget which will obviously reach 76 billion kroner this year, instead of the 91.3 billion kroner originally planned.
Secondly, the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency are Kroner 13.3 billion, the reserve of Kroner 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of state annuity securities for Kroner 43 billion and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to Kroner 1.8 billion.
She was appearing today in a court in Khartoum for naming a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and to deportation, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of having allowed pupils aged 6 to 7 to give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any representation of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punished with whipping.
The 54-year-old British schoolteacher, who works at Khartoum’s Unity High School in Sudan, was arrested at her home on Sunday and charged with assaulting Islam and sedition, under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of pupils to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to the month of September, when this teacher asks her students, aged 6/7 years, to choose a name for the teddy bear of the class.
“Eight names are coming out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” said school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the classroom, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Mohammed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the photo of the bear followed by the caption "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not bear any label with this name, but the problem is simply that of the representation of the prophet considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues, who teaches at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that would be insulting to a religious faith, “I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name,” he said.
Opinion shared by many students of the teacher who describe her as "very caring towards her students" and "who never talks about religion in class".
Remember that the first name Mohamed is also the second most widely given first name in Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
They did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province at the last negotiating session in Vienna on Wednesday.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, concluded a sixth and final session of talks without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
“It is unfortunate that the parties were not able to reach an agreement on the status,” European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger told a news conference in Vienna.
Emphasizing that peace in the region was “at stake,” his US counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
"There is no immediate expectation of violence, but we are entering a very difficult period," he said, noting that "obvious tensions exist."
End of mediation on December 10
The mediators of the troika, which includes the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-speaking province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final negotiating session since the troika was tasked with new mediation by the UN in August.
Americans and Europeans believe that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the Security Council from granting independence to Kosovo, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” Botsane-Kharchenko said.
Unilateral Declaration of Independence?
After eight years of UN administration of Kosovo, Westerners believe that EU-supervised independence is the only viable solution.
Pristina is prepared to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement was reached," Kosovo's autonomous authority president Fatmir Sejdiu said in the hotel in Baden where the "last chance negotiations" had been taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, expressed regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade “belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations.”
“Domino Effect”
Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise was still possible, warning Kosovo's Albanian majority against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
Belgrade said it feared a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the independence wars of the 1990s.
“For Serbia,” he said, “this does not mean that a compromise is impossible.”
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that any decision should be taken exclusively by the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto right.
The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word.
“Only a solution in the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia,” Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
“These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they began: in the Security Council.”
