A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in open access.
The 47 million archival documents, stored over 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were hitherto available only for a "humanitarian" purpose, that is to say individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his successors.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States being completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow research “in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of forced workers,” explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, including Germany, had opposed the opening to the public of these names, owing to the sensitivity of certain information.
Like the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the deported civilians or those subjected to compulsory labor and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual requests.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
