The new gas deal between Russia and Ukraine is sounding the alarm.
A dispute over the price of gas is raging between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk of repercussions on oil exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are conveyed by pipelines, and each pipeline is scrupulously monitored.
Kiev announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, an altercation between the two caused a decrease in supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, Russia’s monopoly-owned company supplying the gas, tried in vain to find an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom said it would increase its prices to Ukraine as it agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for the supply of gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said this would mean for Ukraine a 40 percent increase in the costs of imports from Gazprom.
"It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the conversations, remembering that we are a country through which most of the gas transits," Ukraine's economy minister Anatoly Kinkh told Reuters news agency.
“The fluctuations in gas costs would undoubtedly be related to our discussions about transit taxes (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.”
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused Gazprom's supply to Ukraine to be interrupted in January 2006.
This has led to a drop in exports to Western Europe, thus increasing prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of European Union supplies.
Russia has the largest gas stockpiles, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom supplements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other nations of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
