The Scottish Ministry of Health needs to improve controls on its extra-community employees to check if they have previous penalties, the monitoring committee said.
The warning from the Editor-in-Chief, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was involved in the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Mr. Black also expressed concern that the Scottish Ministry of Health has no specific data on the number of overseas people it employs.
His report nonetheless highlighted other critical checks, properly carried out on a sample of employees from five health authorities.
The Auditor-General made checks on extra-community staff following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Addullah, a 28-year-old Iraqi doctor serving at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after driving his jeep through the gates of the main terminal.
He was one of three doctors who were filmed at the Old Bailey in October on suspicion of being involved in various car blast attempts in the UK.
The Ministry of Health will have to carry out pre-employment checks on overseas personnel, to be sure of the validity of their qualifications, experiences, and work permits for the UK.
Although the Scottish Ministry of Health uses the Scottish Disclosure to carry out previous criminal checks, the agency has no right to obtain such information outside of Britain.
Among the many warnings, the Auditor General's report now states that committees are required to confront the Office of Past Criminal Oversight, allowing employers to undertake controls over various countries.
"While we have discovered that some personnel information has been verified, this is not done every time," the report said.
Mr. Black said that the Scottish Ministry of Health does most of the pre-employment checks it would do itself, but he also added: "Our report highlights aspects where the system can be improved to ensure that adequate information on certain overseas personnel is available to health services.
Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it was “extremely unlikely” that pre-employment checks could identify employees likely to commit future terrorist acts.
He said "the report suggests that the pre-employment checks currently carried out are working well in the Scottish health system and that it is uncertain whether these warnings could add any value."
The Scottish health authorities reported employing 1,161 overseas workers, mostly doctors and nurses.
But the Auditor General stressed that these figures certainly need to be revised upwards, partly because of the problems with identifying staff members with indefinite contracts, who may or may not choose to stay in our country.
The investigation showed that the current procedures of health authorities controls in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian, are quite adequate.
These checks are carried out on passports, work permits and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policy and system of pre-employment controls for overseas health service personnel.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I was excited to do this work in the wake of the terrorist attack at Glasgow Airport.”
She added that the Scottish Government, allied with the health committees, would carefully consider the warnings contained in the report expected to be published next month, and would commit to ensuring better implementation of the recently updated pre-employment checks, valid for all employees, including overseas persons.
