Buses take people back to work, and to fight al Qaeda.
The first bus full of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, dumping those exiles without money or visa renewals, or others hoping the city has regained normalcy.
Some have returned to fight against the militants who have driven them away from their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival in Damascus of 800 people transported in convoys of dozens of official government buses, the terminal was filled with refugees from Syria and Jordan who returned by their means.
“I decided to go to Syria after they killed several doctors in Baghdad,” said Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came back today because I saw on TV and read in the newspapers what happened in Baghdad and saw that the city is safer now.”
“They say the Mahdi army is no longer committing crimes!” he said, referring to the Shia militia of ecclesiastical activist Moqtada al-Sadr, who forced his men to leave for the time being.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shia teacher from the Sunni-dominated Amariyah area, returned with his two children because he could no longer renew his Syrian visa and because the regime prevented Iraqis from working.
His neighbors from Shia to Amariyah called him to inform him that the U.S.-assisted militia had helped drive al Qaeda west of the capital, and invited him back.
One of Jordan’s newcomers is the head of a Sunni and Shia tribe who had to leave his home north of Baghdad because of a grenade attack after he incited citizens to rebel against al-Qaeda.
But he had to go back to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had set up an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh, and that they needed me and my boys.”
“That’s why I’m coming home today,” said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many say they have been drawn to the capital’s growing calm since American troops arrived, and to the continuing training view of well-armed “involved citizen groups” collaborating with the US military to defend their neighborhood.
But still others say they were forced to return because of the visa problem and the decay of the capital Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, expressed suspicion about visas for exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shia prime minister, allegedly asked the Syrian government to limit to force people to return to the country.
More than 2.5 million people have reportedly fled the country because of sectarian death squads.
“We had no problem until al-Maliki came to Syria and urged the government to stop giving visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq,” Sunni said.
“I can’t trust a government that supports the criminals who burned my house when I left.”
The decrease in violence can be partly explained by the fact that Sunnis have been driven from Shia areas and vice versa, creating places where tensions are less.
There are fears that a sudden influx of refugees will once again escalate sectarian tensions and bring back fighting.
Small Sarre, good training.
The smallest federated state leads in vocational training, and even shines by the international orientation of its higher schools.
It is only in one area that a deficit weighs on the Saarians, similar to that of the rest of the country.
"I explained yesterday for the 50th time to a Saarian no, that we are not French" - this is the slogan that the smallest federated state, by self-deprecation, posters for its 50th anniversary.
At this level, France and Luxembourg play a major role in the Saarland training system, which is ranked fifth in the training monitor at the Institute for German Economics in Cologne.
Thus, already by tradition, higher schools cooperate closely with neighbouring countries.
The university was founded in Saarbrücken in 1948 by the French.
To date, students have the opportunity to complete their studies with a double or even a triple degree.
This is evidenced by the high proportion of 15.6 per cent of foreign students.
The Saarland also leads the country's children to higher schools in above-average numbers - many of them without a Gymnasium diploma.
"In Saarland, we benefit from the vocational training system," says Axel Plunnecke, training expert at IW.
More than one in five young people obtain their degree in a vocational school, so the Saarland is more than seven points above the national average.
Also the possibilities of combining vocational and academic training are relatively well developed.
Due to the number of inhabitants, the double-study panel is the second best in Germany.
Despite practical training and increasing demand, however, the number of engineering graduates has declined by a third in recent years.
That is why the Saarland Ministry of Education has forced higher schools to a marketing campaign in engineering science subjects.
"After the first PISA studies, we celebrated a large number of reforms in general schools," said a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Education.
Thus, the government has introduced comparison tests throughout the federal state.
In order for children to start learning earlier, the final year of nursery school is free of entitlement - a model that other federal states are also copying in the meantime.
Only future comparison studies will be able to show whether students' performance is improving sustainably.
In PISA studies in 2003, the proportion of students at risk fell from 29 to 20 per cent.
Overall, however, Saarland has not improved as much as other federal states.
The Bavarians are doing better.
And in spite of the Sarreans, the knowledge of foreign languages is not measured by the PISA studies - otherwise one could earn points in this field.
Because the language of the neighbor is compulsory in high schools - even if the Saarians are not French.
