Lower wages threaten Germany in 2007.
In spite of the strong economic situation, a real decrease in wages threatens German workers this year, according to a forecast.
Experts have cited all sorts of reasons to explain their pessimistic prognosis.
According to a calculation by the Hans-Böckler Foundation, employees should expect a real decrease on their payroll in 2007 compared to the previous year.
"The fault lies with the weak wage development, the increase in the Value Added Tax and the rise in food and energy prices," Gustav Horn of the Institute for Macroeconomics and Economic Research told Bild newspaper.
There could also be new charges in terms of unemployment insurance for the employee.
Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück told the "Neue Osnabrücker Zeitung" that the planned 3.3 per cent reduction in unemployment insurance for the new year was certainly correct and reasonable in the current situation.
However, the National Employment Agency no longer has the right to be embarrassed to ask the Federation for credits or financial aid, in the words of the SPD politician.
It was reported on Tuesday that the explosion in food and hydrocarbon prices had pushed the inflation rate to its highest level in 13 years.
In total, prices increased by 3.0 percent year-over-year.
Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus resembles Earth more than previously thought: the European space probe Venus Express has discovered lightning flashes in the atmosphere and windswirls at the poles, similar to those appearing in winter on Earth.
For nearly three decades, scientists have been assuming that there are flashes of lightning on Venus.
The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has today provided proof - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus bursts at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud in cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprin, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the thunderstorm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be few living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but she remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ESA mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important milestone in Venusian research, as no probes had been on the way for exploration of this planet since the nineties.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles in "Nature" do not only underline the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first.
In addition to the wind whirlwinds already known at the North Pole, the researchers found a cloud whirlwind at the South Pole, which rotates even faster.
The phenomenon recalls air currents in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet called the evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
Köhler defends Merkel’s meeting with the Dalai Lama.
The President of the Federal Republic of Germany, Köhler, demands an end to the parties' quarrel over the reception of the Dalai Lama at the Chancellery.
Indirectly, he criticized the SPD for attacks on the chancellor after the meeting in September.
Federal President Horst Köhler cares about the appearance of Germany and sums up the Grand Coalition to close the quarrel over the reception of the Dalai Lama.
"We must not present to the outside world a divided nation on this issue," Köhler told the Handelsblatt.
At the same time, Köhler showed understanding for the reception of the Dalai Lama by Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) in September.
“Human rights have universal validity, even if I have respect for differences between cultures,” Köhler said.
Everyone knows that Germany should maintain a sensitive balance in foreign policy, stressed the President of the Federal Republic, but defended Merkel against the reproaches that she would organize a new policy of China.
The German chancellor has not distanced herself from the traditional one-China policy.
“China knows that too,” Köhler said.
Foreign Minister Frank-Walter Steimeier (SPD) had indirectly expressed his dissatisfaction with the reception of the Dalai Lama and had been attacked for this outside the ranks of the CDU.
Steinmeier had complained about the CDU's "front-up policy" in foreign policy.
After the reception of the Dalai Lama at the Chancellery, virulent irritations were felt in the German-Chinese relations.
Thus the Chinese government not only decommissioned German Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück (SPD), but according to information from the Spiegel, it also froze the so-called strategy dialogue of the foreign ministers of the two countries.
Chinese Prime Minister Wen Jiabao is now demanding that German Chancellor Angela Merkel acknowledge that the Dalai Lama’s welcome was a mistake.
China refuses that European politicians receive the spiritual leader of Tibet in his official functions, Wen Jiabao thus supported the Chinese position.
The words and deeds of the Dalai Lama would show that he is trying to separate Tibet and other Tibetan regions from China, which also encompasses other current provinces.
Schäuble warns against riots such as those in France.
Street fights with the police, shootings, burning cars: Wolfgang Schäuble warns against riots like those in France.
Everything must be done to ensure that social dissatisfaction in Germany does not erupt in the streets by violence, demanded the German Minister of the Interior.
Barricades burning, burglars shooting police with shotguns: after the serious youth riots in France, German Interior Minister Wolfgang Schäuble (CDU) fears a similar development in Germany.
We must ensure that a social explosive does not build up in our own country and defuse into violence.
We must take this seriously," he told the "Neue Presse" in Hanover.
Not all young people would be able to cope with the rapid transformations of social reality.
The Federation, the federal states and the municipalities were already working hard to reduce the problems, Schäuble said.
This would not only affect the integration of immigrants.
"From integration summits to conferences on Islam, this is already showing its first successes."
But it would be too early for an end to the alert.
Schäuble points out at the same time as in the German suburbs, there are no sociological problems nor from the point of view of urbanism as in France.
In the northern Parisian agglomerations, young people had engaged in serious street battles with the police during the past nights.
Also in Toulouse, cars and public buildings burned.
Greater integration efforts on the part of the German government were demanded by the President of the Turkish communities in Germany, Kenan Kolat.
Given the riots in France, Kolat warned against "imitation effects".
The situation in Germany would certainly not be as explosive as in France.
But there would still be a need to act.
Kolat stresses that the share of unemployed youth under 25 from immigration would be above average.
Above all, more training places should be provided.
Kolat insisted: "We must give young people a perspective."
The President of the Turkish communities added, however, that social control in families took place more in Germany than in France.
Many immigrant youth also do not want to destroy what their parents built here.
Kolat exhorted, "But we must still be careful."
It should be "fast to give young people the opportunity to participate in work and training".
Meanwhile, in the Parisian suburb of Villiers-le-Bel, everything remained very quiet during the night.
Police units were in place, a helicopter was flying over the area with spotlights.
Authorities reported three arrests and a few cars and garbage burned.
Since the conference, a deployment of about 1,000 security forces has ensured calm.
The police will intervene as long as necessary, Interior Minister Michelle Alliot-Marie announced after a visit to the suburb.
On Tuesday night, nearly 80 police officers were injured during riots in Villiers-le-Bel.
The next night, unrest overflowed in Toulouse.
The riots erupted after a traffic accident in which two young people lost their lives on Sunday.
According to the first elements of the Prosecutor's Office, the police are not responsible for the deaths of the young people.
