Musharraf reigns for the first time in civil.
A day after his retirement as army chief, Pakistani power man Musharraf was invested as president.
Thus eight years of domination by the army end.
Pakistani President Pervez Musharraf was sworn in on Thursday for a new five-year term.
Pakistani television broadcast the ceremony live at the presidential palace in the capital Islamabad.
Musharraf vowed to respect the Constitution and act for the well-being of the Nation.
On Wednesday, he handed over his position as army chief to his confidant Ashfaq Kiyani and thus bowed to international pressure, including that of the United States.
Eight years after his seizure of power by a bloodless coup, the former general now reigns for the first time as head of the civil state.
With this withdrawal from the post of commander-in-chief of the armed forces, Musharraf had fulfilled the main requirement of the opposition and the West.
Another central requirement is the end of the state of emergency that Musharraf had decreed on November 3.
Already shortly after his inauguration Musharraf will suspend the state of emergency, according to Attorney General Malik Muhammad Qayyum, and thus fulfill another requirement of the West.
The country's Supreme Court, which Musharraf had occupied after the state of emergency with lawyers from his ranks, rejected all appeals against the head of state's controversial October 6 re-election last week.
Meanwhile, five soldiers were killed in the northern tribal region of North Waziristan in an attack on a military convoy, and four others were wounded.
According to the army spokesman, a bomb exploded in a street near the Afghan border.
The Krautrock fathers are back.
The supergroups of the Germany of the seventies are playing again: the three members of the group Harmonia have again taken their console in a concert in Berlin.
For their return have appeared recordings of their great hit "Live 1974".
Already at that time, they were much better known abroad.
The anticipated sensation then occurs in the form of three gentlemen announced on the evening poster.
Everyone has his little box in front of him, his cable and above all his buttons.
Dieter Moebius, 63, sits in the middle in a snow-white shirt.
He is flanked to the left by 57-year-old Michael Rother, who is in possession of a laptop and a guitar.
On the right, observed by the entire auditorium, Hans-Joachim Roedelius, 73, bends over his console.
Everyone contributes to the noise, among others even a Beat.
And sometimes this is added inadvertently to a traditional piece of music.
This does not seem to bother the gentlemen themselves.
The fact that the band Harmonia plays again has secured some emotion among the fans of Krautrock.
We have the right to reveal it here: targeted polls reveal that, of course, the name reasoned in the collective memory of pop, but in no case in such a lasting way that this group has been so painfully missing for 32 years.
But why shouldn't the German also have the right to celebrate his living legends of the seventies?
Especially since what is misleadingly called "Krautrock" has always been more popular in England and America than in the country of origin.
When the music industry awarded the Echo Award in 2003 to the survivors of the Cologne-based group Can for their work, we saw the questioning German pop faces in the room.
When the Red Hot Chili Peppers also thanked the bands La Düsseldorf and Neu! in panegyric praise, the astonishment had no limits.
Later, during the concerts, Michael Rother jumped on the stage of the Red Hot Chili Peppers as an old friend.
The problem of ignorance at home and transfiguration into the unknown is the only one.
The memory is therefore already taken by Harmonia, because the trio only existed for two years and during this period, the power of impact that was felt was much weaker than what was subsequently attributed to it by others.
Moebius and Roedelius had already played with the artist Conrad Schnitzler under the very promising name of Cluster.
We first played in the cellars below the Berlin stage.
Then in Düsseldorf, for a label subsidized by the church, for financial reasons.
Rother had briefly troubleshoot in Kraftwerk and had finally made a name for himself as a guitarist with Neu!, which was perhaps the most radical German band at the time.
Around 1973, however, Rother followed the musicians of Cluster into exile in the forests of Weserbergland.
There, on a former Weser farm, a 16th-century ruin, they lived as members of communities fleeing the city.
Less ideological than in the "Kommune I" community, where Roedelius had the right to be tormented as a nurse.
Rather an artistic existence in the way of Spitzweg.
