Richard Gere is simply not cynical enough.
With "The Hunting Party" and "Lethal Peace", two films once again address the Balkan War.
But the two do not convince.
Either the projects rely too much on action and on the exchanges of senseless shots or on the contrary they are too tearful.
Here, even Richard Gere in "The Hunting Party" can't help.
The good news first: the war criminals Karadzic and Mladic are still hiding in the Balkan mountains, but it is precisely there, in the darkest hinterland of the Bosnian war, that actor Richard Gere is found.
We had finally lost sight of the most handsome man of the eighties, because far too many nice and futile roles in movies with feelings for women and far too many press conferences on the theme of Buddhism delighted him in the desire to show himself.
Today Richard Gere is suddenly the most important argument to watch anyway "The Hunting Party" - when the hunter becomes the hunted (why do today's movies have to be as long and confusing as collective agreements of locomotive drivers?)
He delivers a magnificent representation full of nods: deep down, his character of war reporter Simon Hunt is what Gere could have become, if fate and the film industry were not so benevolent: a man who has his best moments long behind him, but who, even as a ruined monument to its decline, has nevertheless kept visible remains of his old charm.
But despite this asset, "The Hunting Party" continues together with the German production "Paix meurtrière", which also comes out this week, the endless sequel to failed films on the Balkan war.
"Lethal Peace" can be quickly prosecuted: the film is about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt), who save a Serb from Kosovo snipers, in which one of the two still falls quickly in love.
Although it is welcome that here the Serbs are not for once presented as the sole causes of all evils, this film as flat as a telefilm is too quickly lost in the action and the exchange of senseless shots.
It remains a kind of "Cobra 11 Alarm" without a highway but with a war instead.
On the contrary, we can examine in the perfect example of "The Hunting Party", why at bottom there has never been a real good film about the Balkan war.
The story of the three American war reporters, who condition themselves to track the high war criminal "the fox", could perhaps have become, with another director and another writer (both at once Richard Shepard), at another time a new "Apocalypse Now".
Because the stories are strikingly similar: two males go in a small team into the forest, to accomplish something that the military can’t do and for the two males, it becomes a journey into madness.
One reason for the failure of "The Hunting Party" is that we simply don't let Simon Hunt be the deserted cynic with a heart, as he was presented to us at the beginning.
No, the script must also attribute to her a romantic affair with a Bosnian woman who was later murdered.
Then "The Hunting Party" becomes definitely bad, when the reporter, in the space of the last five minutes, by an accelerated process, achieves what NATO, the CIA and all the bounty hunters of the world have not succeeded in five years: catching the war criminal and leaving him for a just revenge to the Bosnian Muslims.
It is so bad that the International Court of Justice in The Hague should be charged with a crime against cinematographic logic.
In this case, the film has too deep a human concern.
He wants to denounce that Karadzic and Mladic are still at large, and he suspects the Americans and the French (here they must exceptionally agree) of not conducting the hunt fairly intensively because of secret political agreements.
But the well-meaning and the wicked are this time so similar that a famous poem by Brecht comes to mind.
One speaks of a wooden mask of an Asian demon on the poet’s worktable: “Compassionate, I see the veins of the forehead swollen, clearly: how tired it is to be wicked.”
Movies like "The Hunting Party" have exactly such tumescent heads, but they hint at how tired it is to be good.
