These aren't Warhol's boxes.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
Much of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm now leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes" of which the former director of the Pontus Hulten museum gave a copy of the Moderna in 1995.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powdered soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered by right into the history of art and auctioning, as authorized original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum falsely claimed later that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol later ceded to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies dating back to the year 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied without a layer of background to the laminate panels, using a paint roller - moreover, it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These cases have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," suggests the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes as a collection."
Already in July, the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then there has been an inexorable silence.
Manila Rebel Soldiers Abandon
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers abandoned, the same ones who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the president for corruption and election fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The loyal soldiers in power had stormed the hotel shortly before with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been entrenched in the building for hours.
About half of them were in court Wednesday over a failed coup attempt in 2003 — including Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly eclipse himself with about 30 supporters.
The military police, who normally had to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Loyal troops in power blocked the area around the respectable hotel.
The Chair convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the action of the soldiers.
“People are tired,” said Trillanes.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who commanded before the Scout Rangers elite unit, said other army units would soon be joining the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a major demonstration against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila was already the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurrection broke up nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven attempted coups against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
